[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026674&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026674&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


    I just got asked an interesting question that I can't find an answer
to in RFC 882/883.  How does the domain system handle network name to
network number and network number to network name translations?

    That is, given the network number 128.11, how do I find out that
its name is the CRONUS-ETHERNET, or given the name of the BBN-FIBRENET,
how do I find its address?

    My gut reaction is that the name to address conversion is the same
as for hosts -- though some convention is required about what the host
byte values are (broadcast?).  And that whatever the name to address
conversion returns should be fed back as a PTR query in in-addr.arpa
for the corresponding name.  (Recall that simply querying for the
network number under in-addr.arpa gets you a list of gateways).

    But presumably (hopefully) someone has thought about this already,
so what have I missed?

Craig Partridge
CSNET Technical Staff

